16 2021-02-25 ear pain The child was administered the vaccine at about 11:15 a.m on 2/7/2021. She woke up about 14 hours la... Read more
Close
The child was administered the vaccine at about 11:15 a.m on 2/7/2021. She woke up about 14 hours later with vaccine side effects the family was prepared for, including headache, chills, nausea, vomiting and fatigue. This all resolved within 48 hours. Approximately one week later, the child woke up again in the night with severe chills in the middle of the night. It was a sudden onset following a week of feeling well. She had to sit in a warm/hot shower for an hour to get warm. She described it as "freezing to death." She has never experienced anything like this before.

Patient was sitting in the observation area. Patient stated that she was feeling "off" and we helped lower her to the ground into a sitting position. She stated that she felt dizzy and we lowered her onto her back and raised her legs onto a chair. 911 was contacted. Patient remained responsive and was able to answer questions throughout. Patient stated that her shoulder felt like it was burning where she received the injection. She also stated that her face felt numb and her lips felt funny (tingling). Patient was still able to breathe and respond appropriately to all questions. Care was taken over by Ambulance service. After speaking with patients mother later in the day, it was determined patient had a vasovagal episode.

16 2021-04-05 tunnel vision Patient is a 16yo seen for her first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. She was seated in the back seat o... Read more
Close
Patient is a 16yo seen for her first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. She was seated in the back seat of the car. Shortly after receiving her vaccine (within a few minutes), she chose to move to the front passenger seat of the car, and after sitting in the passenger seat she became lightheaded and lost consciousness. Syncopal event was witnessed and lasted a few seconds. She spontaneously regained consciousness, and complained of some lightheadedness and tunnel vision. No significant confusion was noted, her responses to questions were appropriate. Initial pulse was thready and heart rate initially difficult to auscultate. Pale color noted on the face. Initial pulse approximately 50bpm. Breath sounds clear with good air exchange. Patient was placed in a reclined position with feet on the dash. She quickly recovered and repeat heart rate was auscultated at approximately 70bpm, stronger pulse noted. She was noted to have improvement and she was then driven out of the vaccine site after obtaining consent from her mother (who was the driver) and parked beside EMS. BP was 100/50 and HR 68-72, SaO2 97%. Lightheadedness resolved and she was feeling well, at her baseline. She was monitored for 30 min then allowed to leave with her mother, she was at her baseline at last evaluation. Per history review with her mother, she has had 2 prior episodes of syncope with pin removal from hand after surgery and IV placement.

Kept her home from school and she slept a lot. Only vomited the one time. She was fine by late afternoon and all symptoms seemed to have resolved by then.

Close
Admitted to hospital on 4/10 with 2 day history of mydriasis, diplopia with blurry vision, dizziness and balance difficulty. Found to have enhancement of 6th and 3rd CNs on MRI. Patient continued to have blurry and double vision during her stay and mild gait instability. She developed mild frontal headache managed with Tylenol. Her exam was remarkable for mydriasis, mild lateral gaze limitation R>L, mild dysmetria, dizziness and unsteady gait without notable ataxia. No papilledema. Her reflexes were 2+ in her BL UE and LEs. Pediatric Neurology and ophthalmology consulted and followed patient. Eye exam remarkable for bilateral cranial nerve 6 palsy but no other element of CN3 palsy and bilateral dilated but unreactive pupils. Patient treated with IVIG 1mg/kg/day x2 days for likely miller fisher syndrome variant of Guillain-Barre.

Close
Pt. received her second Pfizer dose at 3pm. By 11:30pm she had significant swelling on both of her eyes, mouth, and the start of red splotchy skin on arms and legs. We took her to ER. They gave her 50mg of hydroxizine and sent us home. 5min after leaving the ER at 12:30am on 4/23 she felt a golf ball sized lump in her throat and was having difficulty breathing. We brought her back to the ER. At this time they gave her an ekg, and at around 1:30am gave her an epi pin and an oral steroid. Within 5min of the oral steroid and epi pin she no longer had difficulty in breathing and the lump in her throat was gone as was the res splotches. By 5am the swelling in her face had reduced drastically to 90% normal in her left eye and 70% normal in her right eye and 70% normal in her lip. She was released from the ER at 5:45am and went home to sleep. At 11:30am on 4/23 her swelling in her face remains the same and she is complaining of a headache. She was given 50mg more of hydroxizine.

A 19-year-old female patient received bnt162b2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, solution for injection), dose 1 via an unspecified route of administration on 19May2021 (Batch/Lot number was not reported) as 1ST DOSE, SINGLE DOSE for covid-19 immunisation. The patient woke up the next morning on 20May2021 with puffy eyes and respiratory symptoms (possibly stridor) and self-administered epinephrine, then was taken to the nearest ED where she received additional epi and albuterol. Those symptoms eventually subsided, but what triggered the study stop was her lab findings consisting of hypokalemia (2.9 mmol/L) and hypocalcemia (6.4 mg/dL). In the AE grading scale that the study is using (the FDA's scale used in vaccination studies), these values are considered Grade 4 As such, we met the study stopping rule of a single Grade 4 event and since they were detected one day after vaccination, the site PI indicated that they could be "possibly related" to the vaccine. These abnormalities were promptly corrected and the participant is doing OK, based on the most recent update. There is no report that the reporter could identify that these electrolyte abnormalities are vaccine related and I am contacting you to confirm that this is, indeed, the case. We believe other explanations should be considered (e.g. epinephrine plus beta agonist administration can lead to both hypokalemia and hypocalcemia through beta2 effects; alternatively, or in addition, hyperventilation could result in respiratory alkalosis that has similar effects). The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included blood calcium: 6.4 mg/dl on an unspecified date Hypocalcemia , blood potassium: 2.9 mmol/l on an unspecified date Hypokalemia. I made sure to hydrate and eat well the day of the vaccine. I have had no allergic reactions to any medications/ injections in the past and I was not worried about this one. I didn't take any meds beforehand besides my normal morning modafinil. I have no fear of needles. I received the vaccine in the auditorium about 1:25pm. I felt clammy/sweaty and kept shifting my weight in my seat. I didn't want to make a big deal of it at first because I worried it was all in my head. But I became more and more uncomfortable. I laid my head down on the little desk, no help. I closed my eyes, no help. About 10 minutes or so in I decided to ask if they had water available. I slowly got up and walked to the back of the room. I couldn't even get the question out of my mouth before the nurse told me to sit down. Apparently I was white as a ghost. They got a wheelchair and wheeled me to the space behind the auditorium. By then I was starting to feel like my throat was closing and I saw spots in my peripheral vision. It was kind of a blur from there. I tried to take deep breaths. I drank a few sips of water and poured some on a paper towel to wet my forehead (and spilled all over my lap because I was a little disoriented at this point). My BP was 60s/40s and then 60s/30s. A rapid response was called. They moved me to a cart flat on my back with my legs elevated. My fingers and toes were starting to go numb and my lips were apparently blue/ white. I was taken by the Rapid RN to the ED for monitoring. They eventually pushed the cart into a room and took some vitals and an EKG. They had me stand and move to a wheelchair. I felt horrible but improved from before. They had me sit in a wheelchair in the lobby for a few hours before taking me back and placing an IV and drawing labs (I believe it was 3 hours from the initial reaction). I gave a urine sample. They then put me in a wheelchair and wheeled me back into the lobby for some more time. Then, they wheeled me back to a room where they gave some lactated ringers and a PA and MD saw me. By then my BP and breathing was completely resolved. The MD said he wasn't fully convinced it was just a vasovagal episode because I haven't had issues with vaccines in the past and I was well hydrated and my HR was normal. It partly fit the picture for an allergic reaction/ severe immune response d/t the feeling of throat closing, the BP drop, and the elevated WBCs. They advised that I list the vaccine as an allergy and do not get the second dose, especially since I had COVID back in September.

I started my period for the second time that month, which was odd because it never happened to me before. At that time I was not sure what was the cause of it, I thought it was a bad flu, but I didn't come to the conclusion that it was because of the vaccine, because a week had passed by, so I thought it was impossible. The doctor asked for me to take an X-Ray for the occipital pain, so I did (March 30th) and it resulted in everything being fine. She also recommended for me to get an abdominal ultrasound to see if my uterus was fine due to the second period. I currently took the second Pfizer dose in the same location, but this time around I felt all of these symptoms within 3 hours of the vaccination. I started feeling lightheaded and dazed, my joints started feeling weak, my mouth and tongue started feeling sensitive (fever blisters and sensitive to anything that is acidic, spicy, etc). I have not visited the doctor this time around because the pain is tolerable. I have noticed in increase of joint pain as the days go by.

I received my first shot on April 6th, 2021, and on April 18th, 2021 I experienced extreme numbness with slight pain in the fold and shoulder of my arm. I went to the ER and they took a cat scan of my neck and reported back that everything looked normal - the nurse said it was most likely Cervical Radiculopathy. Then the following morning around 11 AM, I experienced very intense burning in my chest starting on the right side, eventually moving to the left encompassing my entire upper chest. I also experienced a very bad migraine, which I am typically used to but this one was more of a pressure headache between my temples that I felt in my ears and jaw. I made the decision to go back to the ER and to a different one this time. The ER failed to administer a Covid-19 test and to take bloodwork - both faults that family and friends in the medical field have pointed out to me. The doctor there had me receive an IV, a chest X-Ray, and an EKG. The X-Ray and EKG were both normal. The doctor had ordered a Covid-19 test but the nurse forgot to administer it before my discharge. In my IV I received Benadryl and Reglan along with typical IV fluids. I was also given Pepcid and Mylanta. At the end of my visit, the doctor concluded that he thought it was my acid reflux acting up - gastroenteritis. I went home and continued to experience chest burning, tightness, occasional numbness/pains in my body, and very, very bad headaches. On top of that, I could barely swallow - it felt as if my throat was closing. I took Pepcid and Tums and neither really did anything. After seeing a Cardiologist this same week, they ordered an Echocardiogram and routine bloodwork (metabolic panel). I will also be following up with a GI, and I received a Covid-19 test today and am awaiting the results. It is possible I contracted Covid before my shot, but it is also possible that I am having a delayed reaction to my first vaccination as well. Who knows.

While the patient was waiting, seated for 5 of the 15 minutes, post-vaccination she began to feel light headed. The patient shortly after expressing this concern slumped over in the chair, shaking and twitching, for a few moments (likely 60 seconds or less) before regaining normal stature and attention. After assessment, EMS determined this was a syncopal episode related to the patient's anxiety around the vaccination and cleared the patient to drive themselves home after resting on-site. Patient rested and recovered in pharmacy vaccination room for an additional 20 minutes before leaving.

25 2021-05-06 vision blurred I developed a "blurry spot" (later noted to be a scrotoma) in my vision of my right eye a few days a... Read more
Close
I developed a "blurry spot" (later noted to be a scrotoma) in my vision of my right eye a few days after my vaccine. No pain was associated, just a small spot of blurred/rainbow vision. I did not initially connect it to the vaccine, and do not know for sure if it is connected, but it seems pertinent. I was first seen by my optometrist who did a retina scan and found a retinal hemorrhage. I subsequently saw my PCP, a neurologist and a retina specialist. After more scans, I was diagnosed with Acute nueromacular retinopathy. My doctor, who is a specialist in this specific disorder, noted there had been some connections to this very rare disorder and Covid-19, as well as vaccines. Not a lot is known about this disease, but I did have other potential risk factors, such as being on birth control. Hard to say what actually caused it. But the close connection to the vaccine in timing is suspicious. I am personally curious if there are other documented cases.
